Sure! Below is a complete HTML file that uses embedded CSS and JavaScript to create an animation where images from `https://picsum.photos/200/300` fly horizontally across the screen at random heights. You can simply copy and paste this code into a new `.html` file and open it in a web browser to see the effect.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Flying Images</title>
    <style>
        body {
            margin: 0;
            overflow: hidden;
            background-color: #f0f0f0;
            position: relative;
        }
        .image {
            position: absolute;
            width: 200px;
            height: 300px;
            opacity: 0.8;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <script>
        function getRandomHeight(maxHeight) {
            return Math.random() * maxHeight;
        }

        function createFlyingImage() {
            const img = document.createElement('img');
            img.src = 'https://picsum.photos/200/300?' + Math.random(); // Randomizing to avoid cached images
            img.className = 'image';
            img.style.top = getRandomHeight(window.innerHeight - 300) + 'px'; // Random height based on window size
            img.style.left = '-200px'; // Start off the screen
            document.body.appendChild(img);

            // Animate the image across the screen
            setTimeout(() => {
                img.style.transition = 'left 5s linear';
                img.style.left = window.innerWidth + 'px'; // Move to the right
            }, 10);

            // Remove the image after animation is complete
            img.addEventListener('transitionend', () => {
                img.remove();
            });
        }

        setInterval(createFlyingImage, 1000); // Create a new image every second
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
1. **HTML Structure**: The basic structure contains a `<head>` with styles and a `<body>` that remains empty initially, as images are generated dynamically.

2. **CSS**:
   - The body has no margin, hides overflow, and has a light background.
   - The `.image` class styles the images to be absolutely positioned and sets their width and height.

3. **JavaScript**:
   - The `getRandomHeight` function generates a random height value for the images.
   - The `createFlyingImage` function creates an image element, assigns it a random height, sets its initial left position off the screen, and appends it to the body. It then animates it to move to the right and removes it after the animation is complete.
   - The `setInterval` function repeatedly calls `createFlyingImage` every second to create new images.

When you run this HTML file in a web browser, you'll see images flying horizontally across the screen at random heights. Enjoy your flying images!
